{{About|artificial outdoor ponds supplying cooling water for power plants and factories|storage of spent nuclear fuel (usually but not always indoors)|spent fuel pool}} {{Refimprove|date=November 2010}} [[File:Mount Storm Power Plant, Areial.jpg|thumb|right|[[Mount Storm Lake]] is a {{convert|1200|acre|km2}} cooling pond for a power plant in [[Grant County, West Virginia]].]] A '''cooling pond''' is a man-made body of [[water]] primarily formed for the purpose storing heated water and/or supplying [[cooling water]] to a nearby [[power plant]] or industrial facility such as a [[petroleum refining|petroleum refinery]], [[pulp and paper mill]], [[chemical plant]], [[steel mill]] or [[smelter]].
==Overview== Cooling ponds are used where sufficient land is available, as an alternative to [[cooling tower]]s or discharging of heated water to a nearby [[river]] or [[coastal waters|coastal bay]], a process known as “once-through cooling.” The latter process can cause [[thermal pollution]] of the receiving waters.<ref>{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of Environmental Science |last1=Mongillo |first1=John F. |last2=Zierdt-Warshaw |first2=Linda |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2000 |publisher=[[University of Rochester Press]] |location=Rochester, NY |isbn=978-1-57356-147-1 |page=93 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Water in Environmental Planning |last1=Dunne |first1=Thomas |last2=Leopold |first2=Luna B. |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1978 |publisher=[[W.H. Freeman]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-7167-0079-1 |page=722 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> Cooling ponds are also sometimes used with [[HVAC|air conditioning systems]] in large buildings as an alternative to cooling towers.<ref>{{cite book |title=Basic Refrigeration and Air Conditioning |last=Ananthanarayanan |first=P.N. |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2005 |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] |location= |isbn=978-0-07-049500-5 |page=218 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>
The pond receives [[thermal energy]] in the water from the plant’s [[Condenser (heat transfer)|condensers]] during the process of energy production and the thermal energy is then dissipated mainly through [[evaporation]].<ref>U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. Washington, D.C. (1970). [http://nepis.epa.gov/Exe/ZyPURL.cgi?Dockey=9100H0DE.txt “An Engineering-Economic Study of Cooling Pond Performance.”] Document no. 16130DFX0570. Water Pollution Control Research Series. p.5.</ref><ref>Bengtson, Harlan (2010). [http://www.brighthub.com/engineering/mechanical/articles/64576.aspx “Steam Power Plant Condenser Cooling—Part 1: Introduction to Alternatives.”] brighthub.com.</ref> Once the water has cooled in the pond, it is reused by the plant. New water is added to the system (“make-up” water) to replace the water lost through evaporation.
A 1970 cooling pond research study done by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] stated cooling ponds as having a lower overall electrical cost than [[Cooling tower|cooling towers]] while providing the same benefits. They also concluded that a cooling pond will work optimally within 5 degrees Fahrenheit of natural water temperature with an area encompassing approximately 4 acres per megawatt of dissipated thermal energy.<ref>{{Citation|title=Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/springerreference_32156|work=SpringerReference|publisher=Springer-Verlag|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>
== Examples == Lake Anna is a cooling pond in Virginia, which provides cooling water for the North Anna Nuclear Generating Station. This pond has recreational uses such as fishing, swimming, boating, camping, and picnicking as well as being a cooling pond for the nuclear plant. Chernobyl's cooling pond has abundant wildlife, despite the radiation present in the area. Some accounts of wels catfish ''(Silurus glanis)'' growing up to 350 pounds and having a lifespan of up to 50 years in the area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.earthtouchnews.com/wtf/wtf/yes-there-are-giant-catfish-in-chernobyls-cooling-pond-but-theyre-not-radiation-mutants/|title=Yes, there are giant catfish in Chernobyl's cooling pond – but they're not radiation mutants|work=Earth Touch News Network|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en}}</ref> The Columbia station in Pardeeville, Wisconsin is a coal fired power plant with a capacity of 1000 MW. A duel cooling system is used for heat rejection that consists of a cooling pond and two cooling towers. The pond and towers are connected in a parallel arrangement to help dissipate thermal energy at expedited rates.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Joerg |first=Kirchhoff |date=1995|title=Optimized Combination of a Cooling Pond and Cooling Tower System for Condenser Cooling at a Steam Cycle Power Plant |url=https://minds.wisconsin.edu/handle/1793/7801|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |
