{{italic title}}
'''''Liber introductorius''''' ({{IPA-la|lī.ber ɪn.troː.duː.k.tɔ.reː.us|lang}}; '''''The Introductory Book'''''){{#tag:ref|Some sources refer to the first book in the trilogy as the ''Liber introductorius'',<ref>Examples includes: Edwards 1985.</ref> whereas other sources specify that the first book is the ''Liber quatuor distinctionum'' and that ''Liber introductorius'' is the name of the trilogy as a whole.<ref>Examples includes: Meyer 2010; Pick 1998, p. 96; Resnick 2012, p. 15, note 10.</ref>|group="nb"}} is the collective name for a trilogy of books written by Scottish mathematician [[Michael Scot]] in the early 13th century. The trilogy concerns the art of [[divination]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scott|first1=T. C.|title=Michael Scot|url=http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Biographies/Scot.html|publisher=[[University of St Andrews]]|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}</ref> Because the work's prologue mentions the [[canonization]] of [[St. Francis of Assisi]], it is likely that the assemblage was officially compiled after July 16, 1228 (i.e. the date of the aforementioned canonization).<ref name=pick96 />

== Contents ==

The ''Liber introductorius'' is the collective title for the divination-centered trilogy written by [[Michael Scot]].<ref name=resnickpage /> The ''Liber introductorius'' is an encyclopedia dedicated to [[Holy Roman Emperor]] [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick II]]. The work is made up of four parts: a prologue, and three volumes.<ref name=pick96>Pick 1998, p. 96.</ref> The first volume in the trilogy is the ''Liber quatuor distinctionum'' (''The Book of the Four Distinctions''). The second is the ''Liber particularis'' (''The Singular Book''). The third and final volume is the ''[[Liber physiognomiae]]'', which concerns [[physiognomy]].<ref name=resnickpage>Resnick 2012, p. 15, note 10.</ref>

