{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Norwegian Radiation Protection Authority |logo = Statens Straalevern 01.JPG |logo_width = 220px |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = January 1, 1993 |preceding1 = [[Nuclear Energy Safety Authority]] |preceding2 = [[National institute of Radiation Hygiene]] |preceding3 = |preceding4 = |preceding5 = |preceding6 = |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction = [[Norwegian government|Government of Norway]] |headquarters = [[Bærum|Østerås, Bærum]], [[Akershus]] |employees = 120 |budget = |minister1_name = |minister1_pfo = |minister2_name = |minister2_pfo = |chief1_name = [[Ole Harbitz|Ole Johan Harbitz]] |chief1_position = Director, National Radiation Protection Authority |chief2_name = |chief2_position = |parent_agency = [[Ministry of Health and Care Services (Norway)|Ministry of Health and Care Services]] |child1_agency = |child2_agency = |footnotes = }}
'''Norwegian Radiation Protection Authority''' ({{lang-no|Statens strålevern}}, abbreviated to '''NRPA''') is a Norwegian public agency under the [[Ministry of Health and Care Services (Norway)|Ministry of Health and Care Services]] headquartered in [[Østerås (Bærum)|Østerås]], [[Bærum|Bærum municipality]], [[Greater Oslo Region]]. It works as an authority in the area of [[radiation protection]] and [[nuclear safety]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Keus|first=Andreas|title=Statens strålevern|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/nb/dep/hod/dep/underliggende-etater/statens-stalevern.html?id=279760|work=Helse- og Omsorgsdepartementet|publisher=Regjeringen.no|accessdate=9 October 2012|language=Norwegian}}</ref> NRPA fall under the Ministry of Health and Care Services, but serves all ministries and departments on issues relating to radiation.
==History== The NRPA was created on January 1, 1993 through the consolidation of the former '''Nuclear Energy Safety Authority''' with the '''National institute of Radiation Hygiene'''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Norsk samfunnsvitenskapelig datatjeneste|title=Statens strålevern|url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/data/forvaltning/enhet/7822/endringshistorie|work=Endringshistorie|publisher=Nsd.no|accessdate=9 October 2012|language=Norwegian}}</ref>
==Structure== The NRPA is responsible for: overseeing the use of radioactive substances and fissile material, coordinating contingency plans against nuclear accidents and radioactive fallout, monitoring natural and artificial radiation in the environment and at the workplace, increasing our knowledge of the occurrence as well as monitoring risk and effects of radiation. It has regional offices in [[Tromsø]] and [[Sør-Varanger]] and is divided into three sections:<ref>{{cite web|last=Norwegian Radiation Protection Authority|title=About the NRPA|url=http://www.nrpa.no/eway/default.aspx?pid=240&trg=Main_6342&Main_6342=6394:0:15,6230:1:0:0:::0:0|publisher=Nrpa.no|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> *Department of Emergency Preparedness and Environmental Radioactivity *Department of Radiation Protection and Nuclear Safety *Department of Planning and Administration ==International cooperation== NRPA is involved in extensive international cooperation. This includes cooperation on standards of management, but also a growing collaboration on [[research]] across borders. NRPA cooperates with [[International Commission on Radiological Protection]] (ICRP), and [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA).<ref>{{cite web|last=Norwegian Radiation Protection Authority|title=International Cooperation|url=http://www.nrpa.no/eway/default.aspx?pid=240&trg=Center_6393&Main_6342=6394:0:15,6232:1:0:0:::0:0&CenterAndRight_6394=6393:0:15,6257:1:0:0:::0:0&Center_6393=6401:83566::1:6442:1:::0:0|work=About NRPA|publisher=Nrpa.no|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> ==References== {{reflist}}
